The paper discusses compressed sensing (CS) and its applications, which are relevant to several sub-categories of arXiv CS. The paper emphasizes the importance of exploiting signal and measurement structure in CS, which suggests that it may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Signal Processing (cs.SP) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the need to extend the standard sparsity prior to include a much richer class of signals and to encode broader data models, including continuous-time signals, which suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the potential of structured CS strategies to emerge from the math to the hardware, which suggests that it may belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
